{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412785"},"attributes":{"position":15,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12287"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474690"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12287"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261074"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":19,"questionsAnswered":7,"marksTotal":19,"marksAttainable":7,"marksAttempted":7,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:39:59+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.14,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"12287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12287"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.17,0.49,0.22,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106906"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4809"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12287"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89392"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"430"},{"type":"tags","id":"2780"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8168"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19926"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106906"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA mother brings her eight-month-old boy to the General Practice clinic with concerns about his eyes. She has noticed excessive tearing over the last three months. The child tends to keep his eyes screwed up and buries his face to avoid bright lights. He was born prematurely at 36 +5 weeks gestation via vaginal delivery without complications. His eyes appeared normal at birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the child appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His eyeballs appear abnormally enlarged and there are no signs of obstruction at the nasolacrimal sac. The child is urgently referred to a paediatric ophthalmologist, who confirms the eyeball enlargement and possible primary congenital glaucoma. The nasal sac regurgitation test is negative. Intraocular pressure is increased. The corneal diameter is 13 mm with extreme haziness and oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following diagnostic tests is most likely to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Schirmer tear test","Slit lamp examination","Gonioscopy","Optical coherence tomography","Fundus fluorescein angiography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary (or infantile) congenital glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E, including excessive tearing (epiphora), photophobia, enlarged corneal diameter, and cloudy cornea. It occurs in 1:5000 - 10000 children under aged two years. There is blockage of aqueous drainage at the anterior chamber angle leading to increased intraocular pressure, thus stretching the eye and making it larger in size. Surgery to open the anterior chamber angle (goniotomy or trabeculotomy) is often successful together with medication, and the child will need ongoing follow up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate diagnostic test to confirm this diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Egonioscopy\u003C/strong\u003E. Gonioscopy allows direct visualization of the anterior chamber angle structures and is considered the gold standard for diagnosing congenital glaucoma. It typically reveals characteristic angle abnormalities such as a flat iris insertion, absence of angle recess, and incomplete differentiation of the trabecular meshwork.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to gonioscopy, other important diagnostic steps for congenital glaucoma include measuring intraocular pressure (which is mentioned as increased in this case), assessing corneal diameter (noted as 13 mm here, which is enlarged), and examining the optic nerve head for cupping. However, gonioscopy remains the most definitive test for confirming the diagnosis by revealing the characteristic angle abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESlit lamp examination\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of the ophthalmic examination and can reveal corneal enlargement, corneal edema, and Haab\u0027s striae (horizontal breaks in Descemet\u0027s membrane). However, while it provides valuable information, it is not as specific as gonioscopy for confirming the diagnosis of congenital glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ESchirmer tear test\u003C/strong\u003E measures tear production and is typically used to diagnose dry eye syndrome. It would not be helpful in diagnosing congenital glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptical coherence tomography (OCT)\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in glaucoma for assessing optic nerve head and retinal nerve fiber layer thickness. However, it is challenging to perform in infants and is not the primary diagnostic tool for congenital glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFundus fluorescein angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is used to evaluate retinal blood flow and is not typically used in the diagnosis of congenital glaucoma. It would be difficult to perform and interpret in an infant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gonioscopy is the definitive diagnostic test for congenital glaucoma, revealing characteristic angle abnormalities.","Congenital glaucoma presents with tearing, photophobia, corneal enlargement and haziness, and increased intraocular pressure."],"references":["al Faran MF, Tomey KF, al Mutlaq FA. Cyclocryotherapy in selected cases of congenital glaucoma. Ophthalmic Surg. 1990 Nov;21(11):794-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2270165/","Ou Y, Caprioli J. Surgical management of pediatric glaucoma. Dev Ophthalmol. 2012;50:157-72. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22517182/","Malik R, Darrab AAI, Edward DP. Contemporary management of refractory pediatric glaucoma. Curr Opin Ophthalmol 2020;31:123\u201331. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31895153/","Opthalmology: Glaucoma. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital [online]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/ophthal/patient_information/Glaucoma/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89392"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12287"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89392"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T00:48:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T00:48:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4809"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106906"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":